Posterior Simulation: link vs sim

Haowei Lee

12/13/2021

Import libraries

library(rethinking)
Review of simulation for posterior and of difference between link and sim

Import data

# Import the data
data(Howell1)
d <- Howell1
adult <- d[ d$age >= 18 , ]  # filter only adult


define the average weight, x-bar

xbar <- mean(adult$weight)


fit model

model <- quap(
  alist(
    height ~ dnorm( mu , sigma ) ,
    mu <- a + b*( weight - xbar ) ,
    a ~ dnorm( 178 , 20 ) ,
    b ~ dlnorm( 0 , 1 ) ,
    sigma ~ dunif( 0 , 50 )
  ) , data=adult )

precis( model )
##              mean         sd        5.5%       94.5%
## a     154.6012162 0.27030647 154.1692142 155.0332181
## b       0.9032795 0.04192345   0.8362777   0.9702812
## sigma   5.0718588 0.19115270   4.7663599   5.3773577
# first plot
# plot( height ~ weight , data=adult , col=rangi2 )
plot( height ~ weight , data=adult , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5))
      
post <- extract.samples( model )
a_map <- mean(post$a)
b_map <- mean(post$b)
curve( a_map + b_map*(x - xbar) , add=TRUE )


link

# define sequence of weights to compute predictions for
# these values will be on the horizontal axis
weight.seq <- seq( from=25 , to=70 , by=1 )

# use link to compute mu for each sample from posteriorand for each weight in weight.seq
mu <- link( model , data=data.frame(weight=weight.seq) )

# summarize the distribution of mu
mu.mean <- apply( mu , 2 , mean )
mu.PI <- apply( mu , 2 , PI , prob=0.89 )

# plot raw data
plot( height ~ weight , data=adult , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5) )
# plot the MAP line, aka the mean mu for each weight
lines( weight.seq , mu.mean )
# plot a shaded region for 89% PI
shade( mu.PI , weight.seq )


sim

# Use sim to consider uncertainty in th process using Gaussian
sim.height <- sim( model , data=list(weight=weight.seq) )

height.PI <- apply( sim.height , 2 , PI , prob=0.89 )

# plot raw data
plot( height ~ weight , adult , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5) )
# draw MAP line
lines( weight.seq , mu.mean )
# draw HPDI region for line
shade( mu.PI , weight.seq )
# draw PI region for simulated heights
shade( height.PI , weight.seq )

par(mfrow = c(1, 3))         # define figure and plot

# plot 1
plot( height ~ weight , data=adult , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5))
post <- extract.samples( model )
a_map <- mean(post$a)
b_map <- mean(post$b)
curve( a_map + b_map*(x - xbar) , add=TRUE )

# plot 2
plot( height ~ weight , data=adult , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5) )
# plot the MAP line, aka the mean mu for each weight
lines( weight.seq , mu.mean )
# plot a shaded region for 89% PI
shade( mu.PI , weight.seq )

# plot 3
plot( height ~ weight , adult , col=col.alpha(rangi2,0.5) )
# draw MAP line
lines( weight.seq , mu.mean )
# draw HPDI region for line
shade( mu.PI , weight.seq )
# draw PI region for simulated heights
shade( height.PI , weight.seq )

Reference

extract.samples - lists of samples for posterior distributions

extract.prior - lists of samples for prior distributions
